SIMPLE: repair
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Repair
<hw>Re*pair"</hw> <pr>(r?-p?r")</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>repairen</ets>, OF. <ets>repairier</ets> to return, fr. L.
<ets>repatriare</ets> to return to one's contry, to go home again; pref.
<ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>patria</ets> native country, fr.
<ets>pater</ets> father. See <er>Father</er>, and cf.
<er>Repatriate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To return.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I thought . . . that he <qex>repaire</qex> should again.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To go; to betake one's self; to resort; ass, to
<xex>repair</xex> to sanctuary for safety.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Go, mount the winds, and to the shades <qex>repair</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Repair</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Repair
<hw>Re*pair"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>repaire</ets> retreat,
asylum, abode. See <er>Repair</er> to go.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
act of repairing or resorting to a place.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king sent a proclamation for their <qex>repair</qex> to their
houses.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Place to which one repairs; a haunt; a resort.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There the fierce winds his tender force assail⟦br⟧
And beat him downward to his first <qex>repair</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Repair</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Repair
<hw>Re*pair"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Repaired</conjf> <pr>(-p?rd")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Repairing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>r⟦eacute⟧parer</ets>,
L. reparare; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>parare</ets> to prepare.
See <er>Pare</er>, and cf. <er>Reparation</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To restore to a sound or good state after decay, injury,
dilapidation, or partial destruction; to renew; to restore; to mend;
<as>as, to <ex>repair</ex> a house, a road, a shoe, or a ship; to
<ex>repair</ex> a shattered fortune</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Secret refreshings that <qex>repair</qex> his strength.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Do thou, as thou art wont, <qex>repair</qex>⟦br⟧
My heart with gladness.</q> <rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make amends for, as for an injury, by an
equivalent; to indemnify for; <as>as, to <ex>repair</ex> a loss or
damage</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I 'll <qex>repair</qex> the misery thou dost bear.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To restore, recover; renew; amend; mend;
retrieve; recruit.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Repair</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Repair
<hw>Re*pair"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Restoration to a sound
or good state after decay, waste, injury, or partial restruction; supply
of loss; reparation; <as>as, materials are collected for the
<ex>repair</ex> of a church or of a city</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sunk down and sought <qex>repair</qex>⟦br⟧
Of sleep, which instantly fell on me.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Condition with respect to soundness, perfectness,
etc.; <as>as, a house in good, or bad, <ex>repair</ex>; the book is out
of <ex>repair</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Repairable</ent>⟦br⟧
